{
  "answer": "**No works in the corpus open in this manner.**\n\nAfter examining the full list of works, their chapter structures, and the openings of first chapters (or prefaces where applicable) across representative genres—including Old English religious poetry (e.g., Cynewulf's *Andreas*, *Elene*, *Juliana*), Sanskrit *smṛti* texts (e.g., *Manusmṛti*), Urdu poetry collections (e.g., *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, *Bang-E-Dara*), and philosophical treatises (e.g., Charles Comte's *Traité de la propriété*, Vol. I preface)—none begin with a direct address or invocation to an audience (e.g., \"O listener,\" \"Hearken,\" \"Dear reader\").\n\nOld English poems often employ a narrative formula like \"We have heard\" (*Andreas*: \"We have heard of heroes...\"; *Juliana*: \"Hark! We have heard it...\"), which indirectly evokes a shared tradition but does not invoke a present audience.[^1][^2] *Manusmṛti* opens with sages approaching Manu and addressing him (\"O divine Lord...\"), but this is framed narrative, not an opening invocation to readers.[^3] Modern prefaces (e.g., Comte) speak indirectly to readers without formal address. Searches for phrases like \"O \", \"listen,\" \"hear \", \"dear reader,\" and \"gentle reader\" yielded no results.\n\nThe corpus prioritizes translated classical texts; direct reader address is uncommon in these traditions at the precise opening.\n\n[^1]: *Andreas*, Ch. 1, [para. p-868413](/works/cynewulf-andreas-07b573/01/translation/#p-868413).\n\n[^2]: *Juliana*, Ch. 1, [para. p-529b94](/works/cynewulf-juliana-9a2157/01/translation/#p-529b94).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, Ch. 1, [para. p-879544](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-879544).",
